oc:kn_01218294 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When gathering financial data for comp analysis" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Data source priority: 1) MCP data sources (S&P Kensho, FactSet, Daloopa) exclusively if available. 2) Bloomberg/SEC EDGAR only if MCPs unavailable. 3) NEVER use web search as a primary data source." ;
    oc:hasRationale "MCP sources provide verified, institutional-grade data with proper citations. Web search results can be outdated, inaccurate, or unreliable for financial analysis." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_0e14d5a4 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before building any comp analysis" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before starting: define truly comparable peer group (similar business model, scale, geography), choose consistent period (LTM vs quarterly), standardize units upfront (millions vs billions), and map data sources." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Poor peer selection or inconsistent units undermine the entire analysis regardless of formula quality." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_2621e648 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building statistics block after company data" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use quartiles (Max, 75th, Median, 25th, Min) instead of just averages. Apply statistics only to comparable metrics (ratios, margins, multiples), NOT to size metrics (Revenue, EBITDA, Market Cap, Enterprise Value)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Quartiles show distribution — 75th percentile shows what 'premium' companies trade at, median shows typical valuation. Averages of percentages can be misleading; medians are more robust." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_51cb9ce6 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building valuation multiples and selecting peer group" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never mix market cap and enterprise value in formulas. Never use different time periods for numerator and denominator (LTM vs quarterly). Never hardcode numbers instead of cell references. Never include non-comparable companies with different business models." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Mixing these creates fundamentally incorrect analysis that looks correct superficially but leads to wrong investment decisions." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_7058950b a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building valuation multiples section" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Valuation multiples MUST reference the operating metrics section cells. Never input the same raw data twice. If revenue is in C7, then EV/Revenue formula should reference C7." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Cross-referencing prevents inconsistency and ensures single-source-of-truth for each data point." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_8dd29585 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PostFlightValidation ;
    oc:appliesToContext "After completing all formulas and statistics" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Run sanity checks: Gross margin > EBITDA margin > Net margin (always true). EV/Revenue typically 0.5-20x, EV/EBITDA 8-25x, P/E 10-50x. Higher growth should correlate with higher multiples. No #DIV/0! or #REF! errors." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These invariant relationships catch formula errors and data entry mistakes that are otherwise hard to spot in large spreadsheets." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_a44623ba a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building any comp spreadsheet cell" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Every derived value (margin, multiple, statistic) MUST be an Excel formula referencing input cells — never a pre-computed number pasted in. The only hardcoded values should be raw input data, and each must have a cell comment with its source." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Formulas ensure the model updates automatically when inputs change. A hardcoded margin is a silent bug that breaks auditability and recalculation." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_aaaef461 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting which metrics to include in a comp analysis" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the 5-10 rule: 5 operating metrics (Revenue, Growth, 2-3 margins) + 5 valuation metrics (Market Cap, EV, 3 multiples) = 10 total columns. If you have more than 15 metrics, you're including noise. Edit ruthlessly." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Too many metrics dilute the narrative. 10 well-chosen metrics tell a clear story; 20+ create confusion." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_f3d3710c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Throughout the comp building process" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Verify step-by-step with the user: show headers before filling data, confirm inputs before formulas, verify margins before valuation, confirm multiples before statistics. Do NOT build end-to-end then present." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Catch errors early when they're easy to fix, rather than propagating mistakes through the entire analysis." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_fd195c01 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When using Office JS/Excel Add-in to build comp sheets" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Office JS merged cell pitfall: Do NOT call .merge() then set .values on the merged range. Instead write the value to the top-left cell alone, then merge + format the full range." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Merged ranges still report pre-merge dimensions, causing InvalidArgument errors when setting values on the full range." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

